data.content:
Use EF Core 8's `ExecuteUpdateAsync` and `ExecuteDeleteAsync` — they translate to single SQL statements without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this is faster:**
- Generates a single `UPDATE`/`DELETE` SQL statement server-side
- Zero entities loaded into memory (no tracking, no hydration)
- No `SaveChangesAsync()` needed — executes immediately

**Caveats:**
- Bypasses change tracker — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the change
- Bypasses `SaveChanges` interceptors/events — if you rely on those, handle separately
- For the 2M audit log delete, consider batching if your DB has lock timeout concerns:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
